{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6da9d40-bddb-4bef-901d-35ee57c093d0","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps\n/usr/libexec/report_crash   # cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\nThen run your app again — the core file will appear in `/cores/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"54744abd-6d1e-4617-b97e-2480a4e6a83e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no code changes needed.","outputTokens":282},"id":"ea01ba60-e794-4cf1-ad51-d16068a6ba1e","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:55:37.287Z","parentId":"adbb32c2-a3b4-4176-9586-318bc4661f22"}
